title: For Sale:  Scarce and Historically Significant German Luger US Test Trial Pistol 1900 American Eagle
postcontent: For Sale I have an American Eagle Model US Test Trials luger in .30 luger. This is one of the rarest Lugers one would hope to encounter with only around 250 examples doucumented today out of the original 1000 test pistols. These pistols were manufactured in 1901 and 1902 also making them among the first lugers every available. This pistol is in very good condition for a test Luger as most were beaten beyond recognition and were pitted from one end to the other from the humid Climates in the philliphnes and Cuba and most of them encountered today are reblued because of this. This one has a matching upper and lower frame and barrel assembly with the toggle assembly being mismatched to the receiver but matching itself and the trigger and side plate displaying non matching numbers as well. This was extremely common for test pieces as the Army swapped parts to see if they were interchanable and it's very rare and a true collectors prize to find a test piece that is all matching and original finish and they command very high prices when found. This luger is 100% original finish with about 60-70% of its original rust blue finish still present. This gun belongs in a museum or an advanced collection. Below is some information about the 1000 test Lugers. One thousand test Lugers (7.65 cal) were delivered to the U. S. Springfield Armory in late 1901. Most were distributed to U.S. Cavalry troops involved in police actions in the Philippines and Cuba. As the American Cavalry troops had used revolvers (Colt .45 and .38) for over 30 years, the small caliber, complex Luger, was viewed with some suspicion and not readily accepted. There were complaints as to small caliber, safety while riding from horseback, and unreliable action. As a result of these reports 50 Lugers in caliber 9mm were briefly tested by the Army in 1904-1906 and three Lugers in .45 caliber were tested. Ultimately the Luger was rejected in favor of the Colt 1911. The characteristics that separate these U.S.-American Eagle-Test Lugers from other Model 1900 Lugers are: the lack of proofs, the lack of a Germany import stamp and the last two digits of the Lugers serial numbers on the right end of the takedown lever (instead of the left lower side) which this guns displays all of. This serial number 6373 is also listed on the bannerman sales invoice when he bought most of the remaining Lugers that survived testing from the us army ordnance department confirming beyond a shadow of a doubt this is indeed a us test trials pistol. Take a look around at recent auctions and you will see you will never find another of these pistols anywhere close to this price and if you do it usually has been refinished. Will ship to FFL or C&R license holder anywhere in the US. Email, call, or text REDACTED.
